{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868892/1930091101/0505.xml":{"full_text":"I OFFER A JOB\n(Fill out and mall to The Milwaukee Leader, 528 Juneau Ave.)\nName\nAddress Telephone\nI need a man (or woman) to\n(Describe nature of work.)\nThe job will require about hours or days.\nI am willing to pay cents an hour.\n(This coupon will be turned over to the Public Employment\nOffice, which will send to you a needy resident of Milwaukee.)\n\u201cThe endurance of the in\nequalities of life by the poor is\nthe marvel of human society.\u201d\n\u2014James Anthony Froude.\nVol. 19\u2014No. 235.\nPLAN TO SPLIT TWO SOCIALIST WARDS\n\nJOBLESSNESS\nBOOSTS CITY\nSUICIDE RATE\nTotal Nearly Three\nTimes Other Years\nin Prospect.\nUnemployment in Milwaukee\ncounty has caused an unprecendent\ned number of suicides this year, and\nindications are that the total num\nber due to lack of work will be\nthree times as large as that for any\nprevious year.\nThis became known today when\nThe Milwaueke Leader obtained the\nfigures on suicides for the last 10\nyears from Albert J. Grundman,\ndeputy coroner.\n11 in Nine Months.\nRecords at the coroner\u2019s office\nshow that to date 11 persons took\ntheir lives because of lack of work.\nThe figures for'former years on sui\ncides due to unemployment are:\n1921 6|1926 6\n1922 211927 4\n1923 7|1928 5\n1924 311929 ...5\n1925 31\nThe records disclose that only\none or two persons took their lives\nin previous years during the sum\nmer months because of unemploy\nment. The majority of suicides for\nthis cause occurred in the fall and\nwinter months.\nDouble Past Figures.\nWith already 11 such suicides,\nmore than twice the number for the\n12 months of 1929 or 1928, and no\nimmediate economic relief in sight,\nit is expected that from five to 10\nmore will occur during the remain\ning months.\nAll the figures given apply only\nto persons who took their lives for\nno other reason than that they were\nout of work. They do not include\nsuicides where unemployment was a\ncontributing cause.\nCouldn\u2019t Support\nSeven Children\nTime slips, receipts and other\ndocuments proving that he could not\nobtain sufficient work to support\nlii< seven children as he wanted to,\nwere produced in municipal court\nyesterday by Paul Sczak, 43 years\nold, Cudahy, when he was arraigned\non charge of abandonment. Judge\nGeorge A. Shaughnessy released\nhim on his own recognizance and\nheld the case open until Dec. 19.\nUrges 50,000 Duck\nHunters to Ballot\nThis Year by Mail\nMADISON\u2014Votes of 50.000 duck\nhunters caused candidates concern\nhere Thursday.\nWith the duck hunting season\nopening on primary election day,\nSept. 16, #nd county clerks report\ning that upwards of 50.000 hunting\nlicenses have been issued, candi\ndates sought their share of these\nvotes.\nAttorney General John W. Rey\nnolds urged the hunters to vote re\ngardless of party affiliation. He\npointed out that the absent vot< rs\nlaw ix'rmits them to secure a ballot\nfrom the county or city clerk and\nvote any time within 10 days bes re\nelection if they expect to be away\nfrom home election day.\nWeajEiigS\nMilwaukee and vicinity: Cloudy, with\nshowers, beginning tonight or tomorrow.\nSlightly warmer tonight; cooler tomor\nrow Gentle, moderate south to south\nwest winds.\nWisconsin: Probably showers tonight\nand tomorrow in west portion and in\neast portion tonight or tomorrow.\nSlightly warmer tonight in southwest\nportion; cooler in extreme north por\ntion. Cooler tomorrow.\nTEM PE RATTIRES.\n1 a 62 7 a. m 63\n2 a. m 62' 8 a. m 70\n3 a, m 62' 9 a. m 73\n4 a m 62110 a. in. 72\n4 a in 61'11 a. m 73\n6 a m 61 Noon 7 3\nHumidity: 7 p. m., 77; 7 a. m., 89;\nJ\u00bboon. 73.\nTemperature 24 hours to midnight:\nMaximum. 74; minimum. 57 mean. 66;\nnormal. 64. Midnight to 10 a. m Max\nimum. 73: minimum. 60; relative humid\nity. 89; wind velocity at 7 a m., five\nmiles: direction of wind at 7 a. m..\ngon th west; sunrise today, 5:27; sunset,\n\u2022;10.\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nKenosha Captured\nBy Gangdom After\nSiege of Deaths\nThis is the fourth of The Leader\u2019s series of articles on Gang\nland in Wisconsin. Like blood to the fingertips, the trail moves\nnorthward. First the border roadhouses, nested within a few miles\nof the Illinois line, now Kenosha, first city north of Chicago with\nin this state.\nOn a misty night last February, the little band of\nKenosha Catholics emerging from evening services at Holy\nRosary church were startled by the barking of automatics\nwhich dropped their neighbor, Tony Lanzilotti, dead on the\nsidewalk at their feet.\nThe five bullets lodged in his heart and head were\nfrom the guns of his own associates. They silenced the\nyoung Italian\u2019s lips the night before he was to have ap\npeared before a grand jury in Milwaukee. It was known\nthat he intended to plead guilty to a liquor violation and\n\u201ctake his rap.\u201d And he knew too much to be trusted.\nLanzilotti was not the first Kenoshan to be riddled\nwith gangsters\u2019 bullets. Another had been slain before him\non practically that same spot on Twenty-second ave. and\nLanzilotti was the sixth to be killed in gang warfare within\na radius of three blocks of the little red church whose stone\ncross is built into its brick facade and whose steps give\ndirectly onto the sidewalk.\nOne Easter Sunday.\nOnce on an Easter Sunday\nmorning, uncompromising\nmembers of the gang had\ntaken up positions behind\nfour corner posts within the\nshadow of its Byzantine tow\ner and \u201cshot it out\u201d just at\nthe conclusion of the resur\ntion mass.\nBut Lanzilotti\u2019s fate holds pecu\nliar dramatic significance. It put\nhim in the role to which he, himself,\nhad consigned another man six\nmonths before.\nThe story of Lanzilotti, further\nirore. is typical of gangland, wher\never this moving, growing, menacing\nvice kingdom spreads its domain.\nOctopus Tentacles Creep.\nThat the forces of gangland have\nalready begun a successful march\ninto Wisconsin has been revealed\nby The Leader\u2019s investigator. That\nthe remainder of the state is threats\nened, is the indubitable opinion of\nSTRICKEN CORN\nVALUE SLUMPS\n$775,000,000\nBY LYLE C. WILSON.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe United Press\nWASHINGTON Shrinking food\ncrops and destruction by drought of\ncorn worth about $775,000,000 at\ncurrent prices were revealed in the\nagriculture department\u2019s September\ncrop forecast, made public Wednes\nday.\nFarmers are on the shortest corn\nration since 1901. The country is\nconfronted with a pronounced short\nage of potatoes and sweet potatoes.\nA combination of low yields and\nof farm produce prices which were\nlowest last month than in any Au\ngust since 1915 apparently offers\nscant promise of prosperity for\nAmerican agriculture.\nEight weeks of drought in July\nand August reduced corn prospects\nfrom 2,800.000.900 bushels to 1,982,-\n765,000 bushels. The difference\nwould he worth about $775,000,000\nat the market.\nWheat, oats and barley prospects\nTurn to Page Six. Column Three.\nRECOVER 3,000\nSTORM BODIES\nSANTO DOMINGO, Dominican\nRepublic\u2014More than 3,000 dead had\nbeen recovered from the ruins of\nSanto Domingo Thursday as work\ners continued the task of rehabili\ntating the city swept by a Carib\nbean hurricane. Official figures\nhad accounted for more than 20,000\ninjured and 25 per cm t of these\nwere in dangerous condition.\nLet\u2019s Hope Babson Isn\u2019t Talking Bunk!\nRoger Babson sees prosperity returning this fall.\nFor the sake of the thousands of jobless men and\nwomen, let us hope he isn\u2019t a false prophet.\nBut Babson\u2019s optimistic outlook doesn\u2019t help the\npresent situation.\nThe fact remains that there are entirely too\nmany unemployed people in Milwaukee.\nIt isn\u2019t pleasant to be out of work and out of\nfunds even in the \u201cgood old summer time.\u201d\nthose studying the trend of the\ngangland octopus.\nThe uninformed Wisconsin citi\nzen does not realize what is going\non. He may content himself with\nmurmuring \u201cKilled in a drunken\nbrawl\u201d as he re^ds of another kill\ning and sips his breakfast coffee.\nHe may feel secure merely because\nhe does not happen to live in the\nlocality in which the particular kill\ning took place. But those who are\nbetter informed concerning the\ngrapevine connection between such\nkillings, know that what is happen\ning in one county and*city today,\nwill happen in other localities to\nmorrow.\nKenosha is the first city to be\nreached by Chicago gangsters invad\ning Wisconsin. As such, it is in a\nkey position for gangland\u2019s nefari\nous activities.\nDeath Graph Climbs.\nKillings in Kenosha have mount\ned steadily during the past three\nTurn to Page Six, Column One.\nSays Mate Talks\nTo Her by Notes\nLike a deaf mute, Joseph R.\nWojteeki, 36 years old, only com\nnnmicates with his wife by means\nof notes written with a pencil and\nhe will not allow her to prepare\nhis meals, according to the divorce\ncomplaint filed today in circuit\ncourt by Mrs. Helen Wojteeki, 30\nyears old, 804 Thirtieth ave.\nSENTENCE TRIO\nWHO \u2018ROLLED\u2019\nDWARF OF SBO\nThree men who were convicted\nof \"rolling\u201d another man were\ngiven sentences ranging from six\nmonths in the house of correction\nto three to five years in Waupun\npenitentiary in municipal court to\nday.\nOne of the men convicted, Leo\nParker, 713^ Cherry st., was also\nsentenced to from three to five\nyears in Waupun on a statutory of\nfense involving a 16-year-old girl.\nHe was given two three-to-five-year\nsentences in the same institution\nfor larceny from the person. All\nthe terms are to run concurrently.\nThe other two are Richard Jack\nson. 387 Fifth st., one year in the\nhouse of correction, and Watson Pe\nterson, same address, six months in\nthe house of correction. These two\nwere sentenced for larceny from the\nperson.\nStanley Mahnke. 1913 Lincoln\nave\u201e a dwarf who is 4 feet tall,\ncomplained that the three men\nrobbed him of \u2018\u201cSO. He declared he\nhad been talking to them at Fifth\nand Cherry sts. and awoke several\nhours later in an ash can his\nmonov gone.\nJohn Arvi\u00ab. 1011 F ny\u201d nvp\no. pp\u2019-1.-O\" of rphb-'nrr h\u2019m of\nS4O Aug. 3 at Fifth and Vliet sts.\nTHURSDAY EVENING, SEPTEMBER 11, 1930.\nAssess 58 Buildings Here\nAt More Than $1,000,000\nBARNEY SPOTT\nTO COME BACK\nFROM CANADA\nRealtor Must Face\nLarceny Charges\nin Deals Here.\nBarney Spott, wanted here on\nlarceny charges and who was ar\nrested yesterday in Fort Frances,\nOntario, will be\nreturned to Mil\nwaukee tomorrow\nor Saturday, the\npolice announced.\nDetective Her\nm a n Kuhteldt,\nleft to bring back\nthe Milwaukee\nreal estate man\nand former state\nlegislator. Spott\nhas waived ex\ntradition, the po\nlice learned.\nHis arrest was\ncaused late yes\nterday by his com\nmunicating with\nBarney Spott.\na friend in Milwaukee, whose name\nthe police did not divulge.\nAccording to Fort Frances police\nSpott readily admitted* his identity\nwhen taken into custody.\nSpott lived at 1076 Bremen st.\nTo escape service of several war\nrants he deserted his wife. For a\npart of the time he was interested\nin real estate he was a member of\nthe firm of Spott and Schwalm, 26\nCenter st.\nMissing Two Months.\nSpott was living at a rooming\nhouse in Fort Frances under the\nname of John Dinnee.\nHe disappeared from Milwaukee\nJuly 13, a few days before com\nplaints were made by, three persons\nof alleged fraud in real estate and\nmortgage transactions.\nThe complainants against Spott\nwere Valentine Antkowiak and his\nwife, Josephine, 13 Clarke st., who\ncharged that he had forged a mort\ngage and sold it to them for $5,000;\nFrank Makielski, and his wife,\nMary, 1152 Richards st., who\ncharged that Spott failed to turn\nover SSOO he had collected for them,\nand Frances Melinski, 977 Booth st.\nwho charged that Spott had failed\nto make a $250 payment entrusted\nto him.\nBank Started Action.\nSince his disappearance the\nFranklin State bank, which was\ngiven a judgment ot $333 against\nSpott early in the summer, began\naction for satisfaction of judg\nment.\nSpott was a prominent figure in\nthe state legislature in 1027 when\nhe was known as a strong supporter\nof Fred Zimmerman, former gover\nnor.\nCouldn\u2019t Smooth\nMarital Problems;\nDivorce Awarded\nEfforts were fruitless when Miss\nVirginia North, assistant district\nattorney, attempted to reconcile a\nmarried couple, also named North,\nbut not related to her. it was dis\nclosed today in the court of Circuit\nJudge Otto H. Breidenbach.\nA divorce by default was accord\ningly granted to Mrs. Lucile North.\n152514 Kilbourn ave., from Earl\nNorth of Chicago on grounds of non\nsunport and desertion.\nThe couple was married March\n13, 1927.\n\u2018BVnd\u2019 Pilot Killed\nIn Nebraska Crash\nDAVEY Neb. \u2014Pilot Paul Reeve,\n\u201cflying blind\u201d in a fog was killed\nI'hursdav when his airpbme crashed\nnear here. Reeve was flying a lorn*\nfrom Salina, Kan., to Omaha.\nMost of us here in Milwaukee know from what\nwe saw during the cold days of last January, Febru\nary and March that it isn\u2019t pleasant either to be out\nof work and out of funds when winter comes.\nWhat are we doing about unemployment now?\nWhat are you doing?\nHave you given any thought to the possibility\nthat you might be of help to some unfortunate\nfamily?\nDean Inge Advocates\nTwo Marriage Forms\nLONDON \u2014Two forms of mar\nriage, one for persons who do not\nrecognize vows of fidelity and an\nother for those who do, the first\nrecognized by the state and the\nsecond by the church, are pro\nposed by the Very Rev. W. B.\nInge, \u201cGloomy Dean\u201d of St. Paul\u2019s\ncathedral, in a book entitled\nChristian Ethics and Modern\nProblems.\nMarriages of \u201climited contract,\u201d\nfor persons not recognizing the\nvows of fidelity, would be recog\nnized by the state, and marriages\nin which the parties take vows\nfor a lifetime would be recog\nnized by the church, according to\nDean Inge\u2019s proposals.\nThe gloomy dean declares that\npersons entering a \u201climited con\ntract\u201d marriage, with the terms\nclearly understood by both con\ntracting parties, should have the\nright to claim that the state shall\nrecognize their position as some\nthing better than mere concubin\nage.\nUNITED EUROPE\nIS PEACE NEED,\nBRIAND WARNS\nBULLETIN.\nBy The United Press.\nGENEVA Arthur Henderson,\nthe British foreign secretary, told\nthe league of nations assembly\nThursday that \u201cwe hope before\n1936 agreements will be made\nwhereby no more capital ships\nwill ever be constructed.\u201d \u201cWe\nhope the council of the league of\nnations will be able to call a\ngreat world disarmament confer\nence next year,\u201d he said.\nBY SAMUEL DASHIELL.\nStaff Correspondent\ny The United Press\nGENEVA The solidarity of a\nEuropean economic and political\nunion' is necessary to the mainte\nnance of peace in Europe, Aristide\nBriand, the veteran French foreign\nrAinister told the league of nations\nassembly Thursday.\nPleading l in a fervent but com\nmanding manner for the life of his\np a n-Europa project, Briand ad\ndressed the crowded assembly hall.\nCites War Burdens.\n\u201cWar and suffering are far from\nus now but the heritage of war still\nbears heavily on Europe.\u201d Briand\ndeclared in his appeal to the assem\nbly for support of his project. \u201cA\nfederal union between Europeans is\nnecessary for the maintenance of\npeace.\n\"The 27 nations united here are\nprepared for it in principle. Per\nhaps it is a little idealistic but it\nis prepared with prudence.\n\u201cThe European federation would\nnot interfere with the league of na\ntions in any way.\u201d\nSees Italian Pact.\nGENEVA Aristide Briand.\nFrench foreign minister, indicated\nin a si>eeeh before the league of na-\nTurn to Page Six, Column Four.\nReport U. S. Vessels\nUnder Chinese Fire\nWASHINGTON\u2014Foreign vessels\non the Yangtse river are being sub\njected to heavy firing from the\nshore when they pass a point 45\nmiles west of Kiukiang. Consul Gen\neral Frank P. Lockhart at Hankow\nreported to the state department\nThursday. The ships fired upon in\nclude American merchantmen and\nAmerican naval vessels.\nEntered as second-class matter August 25, 1920, at the poetoffice JGE THREE CENTS\nat Milwaukee. Wisconsin, under the Act of March 3. 1879.1 a x\nSPEND MORE IN\nADVERTISING IS\nBABSONS PLEA\n\u201cWhether they should be allowed\nto be meml)ers of the church is\na difficult question of discipline,\u201d\nthe dean says. He adds that\nbreaking of the lifelong marriage\nvows would constitute a scandal\nous and most dishonorable of\nfense.\nThe dean suggests that the\nstate grant divorce for causes oth\ner than misconduct, including de\nsertion, brutal cruelty, habitual\ndrunkenness, cbnviction for fel\nony, and the concealment of bodi\nly or mental defects.\nThe problem of divorce for a\nChristian is complicated by the\nuncertainty of Christ's intention\nwhen he poke on the subject,\nDean Inge says.\n\u201cI do not think that Christ\nmeant to fix hard and fast rules,\u201d\nDean Inge says. \u201cIf a very hard\ncase had been brought before him,\nhe might possibly have said,\n\u2018Marriage was made for man,\nand not man for marriage.\u2019\nWELLESLEY, Mass.\u2014\u201c Spend\nmore money on advertising,\u201d was\nthe advice to business men of\nfered Wednesday by Roger W.\nBabson, world famous economist\nend statistician, at the opening of\nthe 17th annual business confer\nence at Babson park, Wellesley\nhills.\nDeclaring that prosperity\nhinges on the circulation of\nmoney, he said: \u201cWe will not get\nmoney to circulate faster by re\nducing wages, or by discharging\nemployes, or by refusing to buy,\nor by talking gloom.\u201d\nIn giving the business men at\ntending the conference concrete\nrecommendations for bringing\nback prosperity, Mr. Babson said:\nx \u201cI certainly am optimistic re\ngarding this fall. It is just as\nevident today that business is\nbound to improve as it was evi\ndent a year ago that the high\npace of early 1929 could not be\nkept up.\n\"By far the most important\nthing for business men every\nwhere to do right now is to spend\nmore money on advertising.\n\u201cThat will do more to bring\nabout the return of prosperity\nand jobs for the jobless than any\nthing else.\u201d\nREAL ESTATE\nBODY GRANTS\nTEXAS SALES\nMADlSON\u2014Reversing its previ\nous stand which the Wisconsin su\npreme court refused to uphold, the\nWisconsin Real Estate Brokers\u2019\nboard Thursday approved the appli\ncation of the Progreso Development\nCo., Houston, to sell Hidalgo county,\nTexas, citrus fruit lands in Wiscon\nsin.\nSale of Texas citrus fruit lands\nto Wisconsin investors has been the\nsubject of bitter controversy for a\nyear between Lone Star state in\nterests and the state real estate bro\nkers\u2019 board.\nSix companies filed applications\nfor licenses to sell Texas lands in\nWi-consin and the board has sched\nuled hearings on the applications\nSept. 17 aud 18 in Milwaukee.\nHave you any jobs around your home or office\nor factory?\nIf so, won\u2019t you fill out the coupon and send\nit in?\nIt will go immediately to the Public Employment\nOffice and your needs will be promptly met. You can\nrest assured upon that point.\nCan you, will you, help?\nE. J. COSTELLO, Editor.\nSMITH PLANT\nLEADS, WORTH\n$9,450,000\nExpansions Boost\nValuations Over\n1929 Figures.\nAssessments of more than $1,000,-\n000 each were made upon 58 Mil\nwaukee office buildings, hotels,\nmanufacturing plants, stores and\napartment buildings, in '1930, Tax\nCoinmisioner Louis A. Arnold an\nnounced today.\nThe A. O. Smith corporation plant\nis the highest with an assessment\nof $9,450,000. The assessment on\nthe Smith plaat 'last year was SB,-\n640,000.\nThe International Harvester cor\nporation was second with an assess\nment of $6,085,000. Since last year\nwhen the asse sment was $4,680,000\nthe Harvester company built an ad\ndition to its plant.\nAmong the other large assess\nments are the Plankinton building,\n$5,570,000.\nGimbel Brothers, $5,171,000.\nBoston Store, $4,422,000.\nIllinois Steel Co., $4,308,000.\nFirst Wisconsin National Bank\nbuilding, $4,238,000.\nPfister and Vogel Leather Co.,\nthree plants, $4,125,000.\nPhoenix Hosiery Co., $4,071,000.\nEdward Schuster and Co., three\nstores, $3,914,000.\nSchroeder hotel, $3,680,000.\nMilwaukee Coke and Gas Co., $3,-\n450,000.\nCutler Hammer Manufacturing\nCo,. $3,098,000.\nTurn to Page Two, Column Three,\nDETAIN BOY ON\nRARE CHARGES\nA charge rarely nuide by Milwau\nkee authorities brought Milton Bel\nden, 17 years old, 244 East Michigan\nst., into district court today.\nHe was accused of criminal libel\nand was ordered to be given a men\ntal examination after testimony\nagainst him was heard.\nMiss Emily Richer, 151 Knapp\nst., produced a letter which she de\nclared Belden had written to her\nSept. 9. The contents so shocked\nJudge A. J. Bedding that he or\ndered an examination by an alien\nist.\nMillionaire Runs\nfor Two Offices\nCONCORD, N. H.\u2014Albert Well\nington Noone, 84-year-old Peter\nboro millionaire manufacturer, is\nconfident that he can be both gov\nernor and senator at the same\ntime and handle both jobs well.\nNoone has been conceded the\nDemocratic nominations in the\nNew Hampshire primaries for\nboth United States senator and\ngovernor. He attribtned his dou\nble nomination to dissatisfaction\nof the electorate with the work\nings of prohibition. He cam\npaigned on a \u201cdripping wet\u201d plat\nform.\nWhen Noone appeared at the\nstate house six weks ago to tile\npapers for the two nominations he\nwore bis customary diamond\nstudded shirt. Few took his as\npirations seriously then. But in\ndications Thursday were that he\nhad won the senatorial nomina\ntion handily over Amos N. Blau-\nHOME\nEDITION\nFLOSSNER TO\nBE MOVED TO\nHIGGINS\u2019 WARD\nStrehlow and Gaue?\nAre Aldermen\nAffected.\nTwo Socialist wards, the 20th and\nthe 17th, will be divided, according\nto a plan approved by the common\ncouncil\u2019s special ward redistricting\ncommittee, it was announced today\nby Aid. John A. Fleissner, non-parti\nsan, Ninth ward, chairman of the\ncommittee.\nThe 20th ward and the 17th ward\nhave grown to unwiedly proportions\nas the result of annextion during\nthe last 10 years.\nAugust W. Strehlow is aiderman\nof the 20th ward, and Paul Gauer\nis aiderman of the 17th ward.\n23,000 Per Ward.\nUnder the new plan favored by\nthe committee there will be' 27\nv^trds with each ward given a popu\nla.Ylon.as near as 23,000 persons as\npossirW Aid. Fleissner explained.\nThe boundaries of his own ward\nwill be such as to place his own\nresidence in the Second ward. The\nresult will be that he will oppose\nAid. Martin M. Higgins, non-parti\nsan, Second ward, in the next mu\nnicipal election.\nAid. Higgins and Aid. Fleissner\nare rivals for the title of \u201cfriend\nof the city\u2019s poor,\u201d according to Aid.\nHiggins, who charged Aid. Fleiss\nner with attempting to steal his\nideas on poor relief.\nMay Relocate Ninth.\nAt the last election Aid. Fleiss\nner defeated Aid. Herman O. Kent,\nSocialist, by two votes.\nAid. Fleissner said that she Ninth\nward would be relocated so that it\nwould comprise the North Milwau\nkee district. The tendency in the\nredistricting is to enlarge the cen\ntrally located wards and to permit\nthe outlaying wards to remain\nsmaller to take care of future an\nnexation.\nThe city will have 27 wards,\nthree on the east side, 15 on the\nnorthwest side, -and nine on thp\nsouth side.\nThe relocation of the NiQthi\nward will really divide the Twen\ntieth ward into three wards because\nthere will be another division be\nsides the cutting off of the North\nMilwaukee section.\nThe report of the committee will\nbe submitted to the non-partisan\ncaucus next Thursday and to the\nSocialist caucus later, Aid. Fleiss\nner declared.\nPlan to Be Hurried.\nThe redistricting plan must be\ncompleted one year after the 1930\ncensus and go into effect within two\nyears, according to the law.\nEfforts are being made to com\nplete the redistricting plan before\nthe legislature convenes in January,\nso that it can be submitted to the\nlegislature at that time. Because\nthe law provides for 25 wards, the\nlegislature must approve of an in\ncrease before it can become effec\ntive.\ndin and the gubernatorial nomina\nton over Mayor Frederick E.\nSmall.\nNoone prefaced promises of\nwhat he would do if elected in\nNovember with the announce\nment that his election would be\nfollowed by erection of \u2018\u2018the most\npowerful electric beacon light in\nthis country on the summit of\nMount Temple, near Peterboro.\u201d\nThis, he said, would be a ges\nture of appreciation to the voters.\nIn his campaign for election\nNoone will face former Gov. John\nG. Winant in the race for the gov\nernorship and United States Sen\nator Henry W. Keyes, who has\nbeen renominated by Republicans\nfor another term.\nIf elected to both offices Noone\nsaid he would not qualify for the\nj senate until he had served in the\ngovernor\u2019s chair and \u201cput into ef\nfect some of my economy theories\ni in legislation.\u201d","height":"28413","width":"21042"}}
